<p>The National Institute of Mental Health  is the leading federal agency for research and information on mental disorders. NIMH has the latest science on the different types of mental illnesses including overview; signs and symptoms; risk factors; and treatment.</p>

<p>Anxiety Disorder	
Everybody worries or feels anxious at times.  For a person with  Anxierty Disorder , the symptoms do not go away and can get worse over time, interfering with relationships, school work or your job.  Types include generalized anxiety disorder, panic attacks, or social anxiety.  For more information on symptoms, causes and treatment, see The Mayo Clinic on Anxiety Disorders.</p>

<p>Generalized Anxiety Disorder is very common, effecting nearly 18% of the American population in any given year.  It can be mild or severe and fluctuates over time. The disorder often leads to an an unhealthy Cycle of Anxiety and Avoidance.</p>

<p>People with anxiety can talk about it with others to learn ways to live a healthier, happier life.</p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder affects about 3% of the population. For people with OCD, anxious thoughts are persistent and unwanted, causing repetitive behaviors such as hand-washing or cleaning than can interfere with daily life.   Common symptoms also include fear of germs; unwanted thoughts of ses, religion or harm; ordering and arranging things in a precise way; or compulsive counting.  People with OCD have trouble controlling their thoughts and behaviors.  Read more from the American Psychiatric Association
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Bipolar</p>

<p>Bipolar Disorder causes significant shifts in mood and energy.  An estimated 4.4% of adults experience bipolar at some point in their life. There are different types of bipolar disorder, each with a different form of mood change (i.e. manic, hypo-manic, or depressive).  Individuals can also experience episodes of poor judgment, paranoia or delusions.  Watch this Ted-Ed Video on Bipolar</p>

<p>“A combination of medication, therapy, healthy lifestyle and support helps the vast majority of people return to productive, fulfilling lives.”   Mental Health America on Bipolar</p>

<p>Proper diagnosis and treatment is the first step to managing this type of mental illness.</p>

<p>People’s stories about their expriences with Bipolar</p>

<p>Expert Q &amp; A on Bipolar Disorder</p>

<p>Depression</p>

<p>Depression is a common mood disorder that can become serious if untreated.  It is different than feeling sad or grief.  Depression is a medical condition.  Signs and symptoms vary greatly and include decreased energy or fatigue, irritability, loss of interest or pleasure in daily life activities, difficulty concentrating; sleeping to much or sleeping too little; and moving or talking more slowly.</p>

<p>Depression is among the most treatable of mental disorders.  For more information on symptoms, causes and treatment, see The Mayo Clinic on Depression and The American Psychiatric Association.</p>

